Part 1: Brief description of the problem and data¶

1.1 Problem¶

Deep learning is a type of machine learning based on artificial neural networks that teaches computers to do what comes naturally to humans: learn by example. In deep learning, a computer model learns to perform classification tasks directly from images, text, or sound. Image classification is one of the most important applications of deep learning, refers to assigning labels to images based on certain characteristics or features present in them. The algorithm identifies these features and uses them to differentiate different images and assign labels to them. In this project, my goal is to classify images from CIFAR-10 dataset by training Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs). To achieve this goal, I will:

  • Load in the data.
  • EDA - Inspect, Visualize, and Clean the data.
  • Building and training models:
    • Model 1: CNN with two layers
    • Model 2: CNN with two layers adding dropout
    • Model 3: CNN with three layers adding dropout
    • Model 4: CNN with three layers adding Earlystopping and ReduceLROnPlateau
    • Model 5: Resnet50 Model with "Imagenet" pretrained weights
    • Model 6: Resnet101 Model with "Imagenet" pretrained weights
  • Results and Analysis, compare 6 models.
  • Build the best model with tuning hyperparameters.
  • Conclusion.

Here, I will compare these six deep learning models by roc_auc_score because it is generally seen as a more important measure of how good an algorithm is. This metric considers the trade-offs between precision and recall, while Accuracy only looks at how many predictions are correct. It tells us what is the probability that a randomly chosen positive instance is ranked higher than a randomly chosen negative instance. Since we care about true negatives as much as we care about true positives then it totally makes sense to use roc_auc_score.

Reference Sources:
(1) https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/keras/datasets/cifar10/load_data
(2) https://neptune.ai/blog/f1-score-accuracy-roc-auc-pr-auc

1.2 Data¶

In this project, I use CIFAR-10 dataset from keras datasets module.

CIFAR-10 is a collection of images used to train Machine Learning and Computer Vision algorithms, used for object recognition. It is a subset of the 80 million tiny images dataset and consists of 60,000 32x32 color images containing one of 10 object classes, with 6000 images per class. It was collected by Alex Krizhevsky, Vinod Nair, and Geoffrey Hinton.

There are 50,000 training images and 10,000 test images, labeled over 10 categories in the official data.

2.3 Data Preprocessing¶

Before we can proceed with building the model, I will:

(1) perform the one-hot encoding for labels
(2) set random_state, batch_size, number of categories, input_shape, epochs, step_size_train, step_size_test
(3) To work with neural networks, we need to normalize the dataset, otherwise, it could take a lot longer for the network to converge on a solution. As we are working with 32 x 32 NumPy arrays representing each image and each pixel in the array has an intensity somewhere between 1 — 255, a simpler way of getting all of these images on a scale between 0–1 is to divide each array by 255. To make our model much more accurate we can add data augmentation on our data.

# train data augmentation
train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(featurewise_center=False,  # set input mean to 0 over the dataset  
                              featurewise_std_normalization=False,# divide inputs by std of the dataset
                              zoom_range = 0.2, # Randomly zoom image 
                              rotation_range = 20,  # randomly rotate images in the range (degrees, 0 to 180)
                              width_shift_range=3/32,  # randomly shift images horizontally (fraction of total width)
                              height_shift_range=3/32,  # randomly shift images vertically (fraction of total height)
                              horizontal_flip = True,  # randomly flip image
                              rescale = 1./255)    # multiply the data by the value provided
train_generator = train_datagen.flow(x_train, y_train, batch_size=BATCH_SIZE)

# test data augmentation
test_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale = 1./255)
test_generator = test_datagen.flow(x_test, y_test, batch_size=BATCH_SIZE)

Part 3: Building and Training models¶

Convolutional Neural Networks are used for classifying and recognizing images because of its high accuracy and its built-in convolutional layer reduces the high dimensionality of images without losing its information. A CNN follows a hierarchical model which works on building a network, like a funnel, and finally gives out a fully connected layer where all the neurons are connected to each other and the output is processed. That is why CNNs are especially suited for image classification.

In this project, I will build and train 4 different CNNs and 2 different ResNets model:

Model 1: Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

Model 1 is comprised of:

A simple CNN model with 2 Convolutional layers followed by max-pooling layers. BatchNormalization normalize the activation of the previous layer at each batch. Softmax is used as the activation function for the final layer of the category classifier. Use categorical_crossentropy loss function for our category-class classification problem because we have more than two labels. For simplicity, use accuracy as our evaluation metrics to evaluate the model during training and testing.

Architecture:

  • two convolutional layers
  • hidden layer activations: relu
  • BatchNormalization
  • pool_size: (2,2)
  • final layer activation: softmax
In [20]:
# build CNN model
model1 = Sequential()
# first convolutional layer
model1.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), input_shape=INPUT_SHAPE))
model1.add(BatchNormalization())
model1.add(Activation('relu'))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# second convolutional layer
model1.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
model1.add(BatchNormalization())
model1.add(Activation('relu'))
model1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

model1.add(Flatten())
model1.add(Dense(256))
model1.add(BatchNormalization())
model1.add(Activation('relu'))

# Out layer
model1.add(Dense(NUM_LABELS))
model1.add(Activation('softmax'))

# summary model 1
model1.summary()

Model 2: CNN with two layers and adding dropout¶

Model 2 is comprised of:

A CNN with two layers adding dropout at each convolutional layer to avoid overfitting. Dropout is a technique where randomly selected neurons are ignored during training. This means that their contribution to the activation of downstream neurons is temporally removed on the forward pass, and any weight updates are not applied to the neuron on the backward pass. When we have training data, if we try to train our model too much, it might overfit, and dropout regularization is one technique used to tackle overfitting problems in deep learning.

Architecture:

  • two convolutional layers
  • hidden layer activations: relu
  • BatchNormalization
  • pool_size: (2,2)
  • dropout: 0.2
  • final layer activation: softmax
In [25]:
# build CNN model adding dropout

model2 = Sequential()
# first convolutional layer
model2.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), input_shape=INPUT_SHAPE))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
model2.add(Activation('relu'))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))

# second convolutional layer
model2.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
model2.add(Activation('relu'))
model2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))

model2.add(Flatten())
model2.add(Dense(256))
model2.add(BatchNormalization())
model2.add(Activation('relu'))
model2.add(Dropout(0.2))

# Out layer
model2.add(Dense(NUM_LABELS))
model2.add(Activation('softmax'))

# summary model 2
model2.summary()

Model 3: CNN with three layers and adding dropout¶

Model 3 is comprised of:

A CNN from model 2 but adding one more convolutional layer to see which result will we get.

Architecture:

  • three convolutional layers
  • hidden layer activations: relu
  • BatchNormalization
  • pool_size: (2,2)
  • dropout: 0.2
  • final layer activation: softmax

Model 4: CNN with three layers using Earlystopping and ReduceLROnPlateau¶

Next, let's use Earlystopping to avoid overfitting by terminating the process early. Since the goal of a training is to maximize the validation accuracy, so we can set up the metrics as:

+ monitor = "val_acc": value being monitored.  
+ mode = "max": training will stop when the quantity monitored has stopped inreasing.   
+ patience = 5: number of epochs with no improvement after which training will be stopped.

Moreover, let's use Reduce learning rate when a metric has stopped improving. Models often benefit from reducing the learning rate by a factor of 2-10 once learning stagnates. This callback monitors a quantity and if no improvement is seen for a 'patience' number of epochs, the learning rate is reduced.

+ factor = 0.5: factor by which the learning rate will be reduced (new_learning_rate = learning_rate * factor).  
+ min_lr = 0.00001: lower bound on the learning rate.

A model.fit() training loop will check at end of every epoch whether the accuracy is no longer increasing, considering the monitor and patience if applicable. Once it's found no longer increasing, model.stop_training is marked True and the training terminates.

In [33]:
# set up callback
es= tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max', patience=5, verbose=1)
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_accuracy', factor=0.5, patience=5, 
                                   verbose=1, mode='max', min_lr=0.00001)
callback=[es, reduce_lr]

Model 5: ResNet50 Model with "Imagenet" pretrained weights¶

ResNet50 is a 50 layers convolutional neural network included 48 convolutional layers, one MaxPool layer, and one average pool layer. I choose to build a ResNet50 with "Imagenet" weights because the Imagenet database contains a pretrained version of the network that has been trained on more than a million photos of 1000 different item categories from the Imagenet dataset, including several animals, a keyboard, a mouse, and a pencil. Moreover, this model has over 23 million trainable parameters which indicates a deep architecture that makes it better for image classification.

So that's why here, we will train a ResNet50 model with taking the "Imagenet" pretrained weights file loaded and repurposing it for cifar10 image classification. It helps achieve higher performance even if the model is trained on a smaller datatset. Since the training time took so long, in this model we just trained with only 10 epochs.

                                                 weights="imagenet",

Part 5: Hyperparameters tuning and Train Best Model¶

5.1 Hyperparameters tuning for ResNet50 Model¶

Because our above result shows that Resnet50 trained with "Imagenet" pretrained weights file loaded is the best model, so now I would like to build this model with trying 3 different learning rate: [0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]. However, since it took too much time for training with more epochs, I just train with 5 epochs to find the best model which has the highest val_auc score.

While we are creating many models in a loop, this global state will consume an increasing amount of memory over time, so we should clear it. Calling clear_session() releases the global state: this helps avoid clutter from old models and layers, especially when memory is limited.

In [117]:
for lr in [0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]:
    #  clear session:
      tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

      # define new model
      model7 = None
      model7 = Sequential()
      model7.add(UpSampling2D((2,2)))
      model7.add(UpSampling2D((2,2)))
      model7.add(UpSampling2D((2,2)))

      resnet = tf.keras.applications.resnet50.ResNet50(include_top=False, 
                                                      weights="imagenet", 
                                                      pooling = "max", 
                                                      classes=NUM_LABELS)
      model7.add(resnet)
      model7.add(Dropout(0.2))

      # Out layer
      model7.add(Dense(NUM_LABELS))
      model7.add(Activation('softmax'))

      model7.build(input_shape = (None, 32,32,3))

      # compile new model
      model7.compile(loss = 'categorical_crossentropy',
                      optimizer = Adam(learning_rate = lr),
                      metrics=['accuracy'])

      # train model 7
      res7 = model7.fit(train_generator,
                      epochs = 5 , 
                      steps_per_epoch=STEP_SIZE_TRAIN,
                      validation_data = test_generator,
                      validation_steps=STEP_SIZE_TEST,
                      verbose=0)
      
      # get result
      y_predict7 = model7.predict(x_test_datagen)
      auc_score7 = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_predict7)
      
      # best result
      print("For Dropout = ",dropout,"and learning rate = ", lr, ", roc_auc_score: ", auc_score7)

5.2 Hyperparameters tuning for Model 2(CNN with 2 layers adding dropout)¶

In [122]:
# tuning dropout and learning rate for GRU model
for dropout in [0.2, 0.3, 0.5]:
    for lr in [0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]:
    #  clear session:\
        tf.keras.backend.clear_session()

        # define new model
        model8 = Sequential()
        # first convolutional layer
        model8.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), input_shape=INPUT_SHAPE))
        model8.add(BatchNormalization())
        model8.add(Activation('relu'))
        model8.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
        model8.add(Dropout(dropout))

        # second convolutional layer
        model8.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
        model8.add(BatchNormalization())
        model8.add(Activation('relu'))
        model8.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
        model8.add(Dropout(dropout))

        model8.add(Flatten())
        model8.add(Dense(256))
        model8.add(BatchNormalization())
        model8.add(Activation('relu'))
        model8.add(Dropout(dropout))

        # Out layer
        model8.add(Dense(NUM_LABELS))
        model8.add(Activation('softmax'))

        # compile new model
        model8.compile(loss = 'binary_crossentropy',
                            optimizer = Adam(learning_rate = lr),
                            metrics=['accuracy'])

        # train new model
        res8 = model8.fit(train_generator,
                                epochs = 10,
                                steps_per_epoch=STEP_SIZE_TRAIN,
                                validation_steps=STEP_SIZE_TEST, 
                                verbose = 0,
                                validation_data = test_generator)  
        
        # get result
        y_predict8 = model8.predict(x_test_datagen)
        auc_score8 = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_predict8)
      
        # best result
        print("For Dropout = ",dropout,"and learning rate = ", lr, ", roc_auc_score: ", auc_score8)

Part 6: Conclusion and Takeaways¶

In this project, there are 6 parts:

(1) Brief description of the problem and data.
(2) EDA - Inspect, Visualize, and Clean the data.
(3) Building and training models:

+ Model 1: CNN with two layers   
+ Model 2: CNN with two layers adding dropout    
+ Model 3: CNN with three layers adding dropout   
+ Model 4: CNN with three layers adding Earlystopping and ReduceLROnPlateau   
+ Model 5: ResNet50 with "Imagenet" pretrained weights   
+ Model 6: ResNet101 with "Imagenet" pretrained weights

(4) Results and Analysis:

+ Print out results   
+ Compare six deep learning models.

(5) Tuning hyperparameter to find the best model.
(6) Conclusion.

The goal of this project is to recognize objects in photos with cifa-10 dataset which contains 60,000 32x32 color images in 10 different categories. These categories represent airplanes, cars, birds, cats, deer, dogs, frogs, horses, ships, and trucks. By comparing six different deep learning models including: CNN with two layers, CNN with two layers adding dropout, CNN with three layers adding dropout, CNN with three layers adding Earlystopping and ReduceLROnPlateau, ResNet50 with "Imagenet" pretrained weights and ResNet101 with "Imagenet" pretrained weights, we can conclude that in this case, ResNet50 with "Imagenet" pretrained weights is the model that has the best performance with the highest roc_auc_score of 0.98, train accuracy of 0.8 and test accuracy of 0.8.

After tuning learning rate for ResNet50 model and tuning dropout and learning rate for model 2, we got the roc_auc_score increased from 0.98 to 0.99 at dropout = 0.2 and learning rate = 0.0001 for ResNet50. Next we used these best hyperparameters for building the best model to predict on test datatset, print out the result and visualize image with label predictions.

I tried my best and with the result of roc_auc_score of 0.99 and test accuracy 0.92, I think it is good enough, however, because of the limitation of data and the running time was too costly, the models just were trained on limited approach. There are many other ways can improve this kind of project such as:

+ building more deep learning models by tuning other hyperparameters to get optimal results such as: try different dropout at each convolutional layer, try with more different learning rate, ...    
+ or we can run models by increasing the number of epochs   
+ or adding more layers and filters.

I believe these ways might get better results.
